      <hedline>
        <hl1>Scotland Led in Science, and in Tolerance</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Paul Katz letter comments on June 15 Editorial Notebook column on Scotland's educational system (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Karl E. Meyer's ''Genius of Scotland'' (Editorial Notebook, June 15): In the 1930's and 40's more than a thousand American medical students, including myself, were admitted to Scottish universities. Most of us were Jews, as this was a time of discrimination in our own universities.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re Karl E. Meyer's ''Genius of Scotland'' (Editorial Notebook, June 15): In the 1930's and 40's more than a thousand American medical students, including myself, were admitted to Scottish universities. Most of us were Jews, as this was a time of discrimination in our own universities.</p>
        <p>Among my more noted colleagues was Dr. Irving J. Selikoff, who became a leader in developing tuberculosis therapy and also a pioneer in environmental medicine, helping to link asbestos with cancer. Scotland took us in when we were kept out here.</p>
        <p>PAUL KATZ, M.D.  Richmond Hill, Queens, June 15, 1997</p>
      </block>
